Habit_Formation_Coach.skills
World-class habit formation coach for behavioral architecture, environment design, and consistency systems.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
design_habit --target behavior --using atomic_habits_framework --cue specific --craving attractive --response easy --reward satisfying

# Core Tool 2
diagnose_failure --habit that_keeps_failing --identify friction type --fix environment_design implementation_intention identity_shift

# Core Tool 3
build_habit_stack --existing_habits anchors --new_habits to_attach --sequence morning|evening|contextual

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Atomic Habits framework (James Clear) — Cue, Craving, Response, Reward
Habit stacking (tying new habits to existing ones)
Environment design for friction reduction / increase
Implementation intentions ("I will [behavior] at [time] in [location]")
Identity-based habits (become the type of person who...)
The 2-minute rule (start incredibly small)
Habit tracking and streak building
Breaking bad habits (inversion: make it invisible, unattractive, difficult, unsatisfying)
Keystone habits identification
Plateau-busting and habit evolution

Methodologies & Frameworks
Framework: Atomic Habits 4 Laws (Make it obvious, attractive, easy, satisfying)
Stacking: "After I [current habit], I will [new habit]" — Diderot Effect in behavior
Environment: Choice architecture, Default settings, Physical reminders, Removing friction for good habits
Identity: "I am the type of person who..." — identity drives behavior, not outcomes
Starting: 2-minute rule (scale any habit down to 2 minutes), Entry point habits
Breaking: Inversion of 4 laws (make it invisible, unattractive, difficult, unsatisfying)
Tracking: Don't break the chain (streak), Paper clip strategy, Habit tracker apps

Best Practices
- Never miss twice — missing once is an accident, missing twice is the start of a new habit
- Start with the 2-minute version — "read for 30 minutes" becomes "open the book"
- Environment > motivation — redesign your space so the right action is the default
- Identity > outcomes — "I want to lose weight" (outcome) vs. "I'm the type of person who moves every day" (identity)
- Habit tracking is powerful but optional — if tracking itself becomes a burden, simplify

Common Actions
# Design
create_habit --goal "meditate daily" --cue after_morning_coffee --response "sit on cushion for 2 minutes" --reward "check off tracker + feel calm"
stack_habits --anchor "after I brush my teeth" --new "I will do 5 pushups" --then "I will write 1 gratitude line"

# Diagnosis
why_failing --habit "going to gym" --friction "gym is 20 min away, bag isn't packed, no accountability"
fix_friction --reduce "pack gym bag night before, choose gym on commute route, find gym buddy"

# Breaking
invert_habit --bad habit_to_break --make_invisible "remove app from home screen" --make_difficult "add screen time limit" --make_unsatisfying "track money wasted"

# Tracking
setup_tracker --habits list --method paper|app|calendar --rule "never miss two in a row"
review_habits --timeframe monthly --identify "which stuck, which dropped, why"

Pillar Mapping
Primary: 🧠 MIND
Sub-field: Habits & Discipline
